🧠 Sr. Design Engineer – 30 Min Recruiter Screen (Your Custom Guide)

🎯 1. Your Positioning (What You Are)

You are not just a design engineer — position yourself as:

“A manufacturing-focused design engineer with deep experience in tooling, materials, and production systems.”

💡 Your edge vs typical candidates:
	•	Aerospace rigor (Boeing, Raytheon, Lockheed)
	•	Hands-on manufacturing + shop floor exposure
	•	Strong design + analysis + production bridge

⸻

🗣️ 2. Your 60-Second Pitch (Use This)

“I’m currently a Senior Tooling Design Engineer at Boeing, where I design and deliver production tooling from concept through release, including analysis and shop-floor implementation.

Across my career at Boeing, Raytheon, and Lockheed, I’ve consistently worked at the intersection of design and manufacturing—whether that’s tooling design, materials and process development, or supporting production environments.

A big part of my experience is designing under real-world constraints—materials, cost, and manufacturability—and working closely with technicians and production teams to make designs successful in practice.

That’s why this role at Fibrelite stood out—it’s very much about practical engineering and product design that has to perform reliably in real environments.”

⸻

🔧 3. Your Story (How to Frame Your Experience)

✈️ Boeing → DESIGN + OWNERSHIP

Emphasize:
	•	Full lifecycle ownership (concept → release)
	•	Tooling that directly impacts production
	•	Stress analysis + validation

Say:

“I own tooling designs end-to-end and ensure they’re actually usable on the floor.”

⸻

🚀 Raytheon Technologies → MATERIALS + PROCESSES

Emphasize:
	•	SME-level ownership (laser welding)
	•	High-reliability systems
	•	Equipment + process scaling

Say:

“I’ve led both process development and production sustainment in high-reliability environments.”

⸻

🛰️ Lockheed Martin → MANUFACTURING + OPTIMIZATION

Emphasize:
	•	Process improvement
	•	Automation + yield improvement
	•	Shop floor implementation

Say:

“I’ve spent a lot of time improving real production systems, not just designing in isolation.”

⸻

💬 4. Answers You Should Nail

“Tell me about your experience”

👉 Structure:
	•	Tooling design (Boeing)
	•	Materials/process (Raytheon)
	•	Manufacturing optimization (Lockheed)

Key phrase to include:

“I’ve consistently worked where design meets manufacturing.”

⸻

“Why this role?”

“I’m especially interested in roles where engineering is closely tied to manufacturing and real-world product performance. Fibrelite’s focus on structural composite products used in critical infrastructure really aligns with my background in high-reliability systems and practical design.”

⸻

“Manufacturing experience?”

This is your strongest area—lean in hard:

“A large part of my career has been supporting production environments—working with technicians, resolving issues on the floor, improving processes, and ensuring designs are actually manufacturable and scalable.”

⸻

“What tools do you use?”

Keep it clean:
	•	CATIA V5 (primary)
	•	Analysis (stress, tolerance stack-ups)
	•	SPC / process tools
	•	Hands-on validation + testing

⸻

“Salary expectations?”

Have a range ready (don’t hesitate):

“Based on my experience and the scope, I’d expect something in the range of $X–$Y, but I’m flexible depending on the overall package.”

⸻

🧩 5. Your Key Strengths (Translate to Their World)

Map your experience → their needs:

Your Background	Their Need
Tooling design	Product + structural design
Aerospace rigor	Safety-critical infrastructure
Manufacturing support	Plant collaboration
Materials expertise	Composite product understanding
Process improvement	Cost + efficiency

👉 Say things like:
	•	“designing for manufacturability”
	•	“working with production teams”
	•	“balancing performance and cost”

⸻

⚠️ 6. What to Downplay (Important)

Avoid over-emphasizing:
	•	Space/aerospace complexity
	•	Deep theory
	•	Pure analysis work

👉 They want:

practical, buildable, durable designs

⸻

❓ 7. Questions to Ask (Pick 2–3)

Best tailored for you:
	•	“How closely does this role work with the manufacturing team in Smithfield?”
	•	“Is the focus more on new product development or improving existing designs?”
	•	“What are the biggest challenges the team is facing right now?”
	•	“What does success look like in the first 6 months?”

⸻

🧭 8. Final Reminder (This Is the Game)

They are NOT asking:

“Is this person brilliant?”

They ARE asking:

“Can this person design real products, work with a plant, and communicate well?”

⸻

